<font color="#FF0000">TO TAO</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jun 27  6:23:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hey Tao,<br><br>
Thanks for your message. I have no quarrel with your description of worldwide communist aims.<br><br>
However, I am unable to associate your view of communist hegemony in regards to Vietnam.<br><br>
The Vietnamese people had fought all types of foreigners for thousands of years in order to control their own destiny. This began long before communism. Ho Chi Minh was a nationalist before he was a communist.<br><br>
If the communists did not consider civilians as being important, how about men like American General Curtis Lemay saying that we should bomb Vietnam back into the stone age? How much consideration do others show for non combatants with such talk?<br><br>
To borrow a phrase from Stephen Crane, I have been to the circus to see the elephant. I have seen the destruction. It is tormenting to me to recall, day after day, injustices against the people by *us*.<br><br>
It is one thing to claim that the communists didn't worry about killing civilians in order to gain their objectives. It is quite another for America - whose mission was to win the hearts and minds of the Vietnamese - to have soldiers who showed a disregard towards the people we were supposed to be helping.<br><br>
I know all the excuses. As one who served in the military, I refuse to hear them. We are Americans. We should hold ourselves to the highest of standards. If we were unable to accomplish this - then we didn't belong in any foreign country attempting to exert influence.<br><br>
I need no convincing of the evil of totalitarian communism. I rejoice at its downfall. However, I strongly object to United States sanctions, over the years, of men like Somoza, Marcos, Noriega, and Diem. There was no side in the Vietnam War that was deserving of one American casualty. It was not our fight.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


